AB  - This article summarizes the evidence available to date for using musical learning paradigms to improve cognitive deficits especially in specific reading disorders. Amongst various explanatory hypotheses of dyslexia, one that predominates considers dyslexia as a phonological disorder and recent works have shown that the core deficit in dyslexia would not involve deficient representation but impaired access to them. At the cerebral level, this deficit could be due to defective connectivity between the relevant brain regions. It has been shown that musical training, especially when various sensory channels and motor (singing or instrumental practice) output are simultaneously involved, facilitates cross-modal integration and reinforces processing within each modality. Finally, we present preliminary results of a study from our group with intensive musical training over 3 successive days in dyslexic children. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
