AB  - Reviews the book, The Oxford handbook of auditory science: The ear, The auditory brain, Hearing (3 volumes) edited by D. Moore, P. Fuchs, A. Palmer and A. Rees (2010). The editors of this book undertakes the perilous responsibility of offering a comprehensive and updated account of auditory neuroscience research. This handbook includes three volumes devoted to "The Ear", "The Auditory Brain" and "Hearing". In the first volume on "The Ear", the complexity of the auditory neural system is presented in a structured manner that makes the information accessible to readers with a wide range of interests and experiences. Next, the volume on "The Auditory Brain" shows a rationally organized view on auditory processing in the brain. The third volume of this series on "Hearing" takes a more psychological approach. It covers almost all aspects, from psychoacoustics to higher-level cognition such as speech or music perception, cross-modal integration, and auditory attention. Thus, this set of books may be most useful to graduate students and investigators with fair awareness of issues in the field of auditory neuroscience. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
