AB  - The articles in this special issue discuss and describe research related to information exchange with existing to truly ubiquitous systems. Some of the topics discussed in this special issue are: the implications associated with the exchange of health information in a ubicomp world; the continued spread of information technology and considers the fundamental need for various organizations to address security and privacy concerns for stored information; the use of a music recommender system focusing on privacy, personalization, and user profiling. These concepts are crucial to help further our understanding of ubicomp systems; the social implications of information exchange in a ubiquitous society, in particular the use of an e-voting system; how control and unlimited collection of information in a ubiquitous world will be complex; consumer reactions to radio frequency identification (RFID) in a retail environment; the notion of a cross-modal display as a proposal for enhancing the privacy of public information displays in a ubiquitous environment; and the use of ethnographies to understand the contextual influence on the user experience in public and domestic environments. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
